---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Speaking — Maksym Voitko" description="Talk topics, speaker bios, and booking info for Maksym Voitko — AI, data engineering, and engineering leadership." activeNav="speaking">
  <div class="speaking-page">
  <div class="page-header">
    <h1>I Speak About <span class="highlight">AI &amp; Data</span></h1>
  </div>

  <article class="speaking">
    <section>
      <h2>Talk Topics</h2>

      <div class="talk">
        <div class="talk-header">
          <h3>Building Multi-Agent RAG Systems in Production</h3>
        </div>
        <p>How do you go from a proof-of-concept chatbot to an enterprise-grade retrieval-augmented generation system? This talk walks through designing vectorisation pipelines, choosing retrieval strategies (dense, sparse, hybrid), and orchestrating multiple specialised agents with LangChain and LlamaIndex. I cover the hard lessons learned shipping multi-agent RAG at scale &mdash; from chunking trade-offs and embedding model selection to guardrails, evaluation frameworks, and the operational patterns that keep production AI reliable.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="talk">
        <div class="talk-header">
          <h3>Zero to MLOps: Building ML Infrastructure from Scratch</h3>
        </div>
        <p>Most ML teams start with notebooks and good intentions. This talk is about what comes next: standing up production ML infrastructure on Kubernetes with Kubeflow, orchestrating training and feature pipelines through Airflow, versioning data and models with DVC, and the YAML DAG factory pattern that lets data scientists ship pipelines without writing boilerplate code. I share the architecture decisions, tooling trade-offs, and cultural shifts that turned a scrappy data team into a self-service ML platform.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="talk">
        <div class="talk-header">
          <h3>From QA to Head of AI: The Non-Linear Engineering Career</h3>
        </div>
        <p>My career started in quality assurance, moved through test automation and back-end engineering, took a detour into computer vision, and landed at leading AI teams. This talk is about the power of non-linear career paths &mdash; how switching domains forces you to learn faster, why breadth of experience makes you a better technical leader, and how to navigate the uncertainty of reinventing yourself every few years. Practical advice for engineers who feel stuck in a single lane.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="talk">
        <div class="talk-header">
          <h3>AI-Powered Computer Vision in Sports Broadcasting</h3>
        </div>
        <p>The AJNA system stitches two 4K camera feeds into a single panoramic video and uses computer vision to track players, measure ball speed, and analyse team formations &mdash; all in real time, without human operators. This talk covers the end-to-end pipeline: camera calibration and image stitching, object detection and tracking models, the engineering challenges of processing high-resolution video at broadcast latency, and how we built a system that turns raw footage into structured sports analytics.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="talk">
        <div class="talk-header">
          <h3>Leading AI Teams: Building Cross-Functional Engineering Culture</h3>
        </div>
        <p>AI teams are not typical software teams. They blend ML engineers, software developers, data engineers, and DevOps specialists &mdash; each with different workflows, tools, and definitions of &ldquo;done&rdquo;. This talk shares what I have learned about hiring for cognitive diversity, designing interview loops that actually predict on-the-job performance, mentoring engineers across disciplines, and creating a team culture where research rigour and shipping velocity coexist. Concrete frameworks for managers building or scaling AI organisations.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Speaker Bio</h2>
      <p class="bio-intro">Copy-paste versions for event organisers. Pick the length that fits your programme.</p>

      <div class="bio-card">
        <div class="bio-header">
          <h3>Short Bio</h3>
          <span class="bio-length">~50 words</span>
        </div>
        <div class="bio-text">Maksym Voitko is a technology leader and staff-level engineer with over ten years of experience in AI, data engineering and back-end development. He is an R&amp;D Tech Lead at Monday.com, where he works on reporting infrastructure at scale. Previously, he built multi-agent RAG systems, MLOps platforms, and AI-powered computer vision products across multiple industries.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="bio-card">
        <div class="bio-header">
          <h3>Medium Bio</h3>
          <span class="bio-length">~100 words</span>
        </div>
        <div class="bio-text">Maksym Voitko is a technology leader and staff-level engineer with over ten years of experience spanning AI, data engineering and back-end development. He is an R&amp;D Tech Lead at Monday.com, working on the Reporting &amp; Widgets team. Previously, as Head of Data &amp; AI at Honeycomb Software, he led a cross-functional team building end-to-end data and AI products, including multi-agent RAG systems and vectorisation pipelines. Earlier, he designed ML recommendation platforms, built MLOps infrastructure from scratch with Kubernetes and Kubeflow, and led the AJNA sports AI system &mdash; a 4K computer vision platform for real-time player and ball tracking. Maksym holds a Master&rsquo;s in Computer Engineering from KPI, Kyiv.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="bio-card">
        <div class="bio-header">
          <h3>Long Bio</h3>
          <span class="bio-length">~200 words</span>
        </div>
        <div class="bio-text">Maksym Voitko is a technology leader and staff-level engineer with over ten years of experience in AI, data engineering and back-end development. He is an R&amp;D Tech Lead at Monday.com, where he works on the Reporting &amp; Widgets team tackling widget governance, scaling infrastructure, and performance &mdash; bringing deep expertise in building data platforms and AI systems from the ground up.

Previously, as the first employee of the Data &amp; AI department at Honeycomb Software, Maksym built the team from scratch &mdash; setting up hiring, development, and performance processes and growing it to twelve engineers. As Head of Data &amp; AI he led that cross-functional group to build end-to-end data and AI products, designing vectorisation pipelines and deploying multi-agent RAG systems that power enterprise knowledge retrieval. Before that, as Research Development Team &amp; Tech Lead at GR8 Tech, he built an ML recommendation platform that measurably increased user engagement and created MLOps infrastructure from scratch using Kubernetes, Kubeflow, Airflow and DVC &mdash; including a YAML-driven DAG factory that let data scientists ship pipelines without writing boilerplate code.

Maksym also led the AJNA sports AI project at SoftConstruct, where his team built a computer vision system that stitches two 4K camera feeds into panoramic video and tracks players and ball movement in real time. His career spans quality assurance, test automation, back-end engineering, data engineering and AI leadership. He holds a Master&rsquo;s in Computer Engineering from the National Technical University of Ukraine &ldquo;Kyiv Polytechnic Institute&rdquo;.</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Past Talks</h2>
      <div class="talk placeholder">
        <p>Upcoming talks will be listed here.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="cta-section">
      <h2>Get in Touch</h2>
      <p>Interested in having me speak at your event, conference, or podcast?</p>
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="mailto:max.voitko@gmail.com?subject=Speaking%20Invitation">Invite me to speak &rarr;</a>
    </section>
  </article>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .speaking-page {
    max-width: 800px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding-top: calc(64px + 4rem);
    padding-bottom: 6rem;
  }

  .page-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 1rem;
  }
  .page-header h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 3rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    letter-spacing: -0.03em;
  }

  .speaking section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }
  .speaking h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--accent);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    padding-bottom: 0.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }
  .speaking p {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: var(--text);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* ── Talk Cards ── */
  .talk {
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    transition: all 0.3s;
  }
  .talk:hover {
    background: var(--bg-card-hover);
    border-color: var(--accent-border);
  }
  .talk-header {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .talk-header h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text);
  }
  .talk p {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.65;
  }
  .talk.placeholder {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 2rem;
  }
  .talk.placeholder p {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
  }

  /* ── Bio Cards ── */
  .bio-intro {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
  }
  .bio-card {
    background: var(--bg-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius);
    padding: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    transition: all 0.3s;
  }
  .bio-card:hover {
    background: var(--bg-card-hover);
    border-color: var(--accent-border);
  }
  .bio-header {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }
  .bio-header h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text);
  }
  .bio-length {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    background: var(--accent-dim);
    border: 1px solid var(--accent-border);
    border-radius: 6px;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.5rem;
  }
  .bio-text {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.82rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    padding: 1rem;
    background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.15);
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
    white-space: pre-wrap;
  }

  /* ── CTA Section ── */
  .cta-section {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 2rem 0;
  }
  .cta-section p {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
  }

  @media (max-width: 768px) {
    .speaking-page { padding-top: calc(64px + 2rem); }
    .talk { padding: 1.25rem; }
    .bio-card { padding: 1.25rem; }
    .bio-text { padding: 0.75rem; font-size: 0.78rem; }
    .bio-header { flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 0.5rem; }
  }
</style>
